[1] Mexico
Date: Mon 27 Mar 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: El Porvenir, Mexico, 24 Mar 2006 [translated by Mod.JGM, edited]
<http://www.elporvenir.com.mx/notas.asp?nota_id=58085>

1st death caused by dengue fever is reported
--------------------------------------------
Authorities from Nuevo Leon Health Secretariat reported the 1st death
caused by dengue hemorrhagic fever. In an unprecedented case, authorities
from Nuevo Leon Health Secretariat reported the 1st death caused by dengue
hemorrhagic fever. There was a rumor around for a couple of weeks, which
was confirmed yesterday [23 Mar 2006], stating that a 15 year old girl from
Linares community died because of dengue fever.
The 1st fatal case of hemorrhagic dengue fever in Nuevo Leon was confirmed
by Mr Ricardo Huerta-Gallaga, sub-secretary for disease prevention and control.
According to health authorities, the disease that caused the death of the
girl was dengue fever, according to the results of the autopsy. The girl,
who lived in Los Angeles peripheral area in Linares, developed a clinical
condition with pneumonia and acute tubular necrosis, a kidney complication,
which confirms (suggests) the presence of dengue fever. This is the 1st
fatal case caused by this condition in Nuevo Leon since 1999. The autopsy
was performed in the University Hospital, where she died, but the Federal
Health Secretariat will determine what type of dengue the patient had.
Mr Huerta-Gallaga emphasized that this year [2006] is favorable for having
a higher frequency of such cases, since last winter [2005] was not as
intense as usual, and mosquitoes were not exterminated as they were in the
past. It is estimated that 26 states in this country are vulnerable. In
Nuevo Leon, it is estimated that some 3000 cases may be reported throughout
the year. With respect to additional similar cases, authorities confirmed 2
dengue fever cases, one corresponding to hemorrhagic dengue fever, which
affected the deceased patient, and another case of classic dengue fever,
affecting a 33-year-old person in La Florida area.
--
