[2] Paraguay
Date: 25 Mar 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Pais, Diario Ultima Hora Digital, Paraguay, 25 Mar 2006 [translated
by Mod.JGM, edited]
<http://www.ultimahora.com/template.asp?notic=228308>

Two cases of dengue fever prompt alert
--------------------------------------
The 1st 2 cases of dengue fever for this year [2006] were confirmed
yesterday [24 Mar 2006] by the laboratory: a 26 year old woman in downtown
Asunci and an 11 year old boy in Itaugu. The occurrence of the disease was
no surprise for anybody. Heat and frequent rainfalls, together with the
existence of mosquito breeding sites in one out of 10 houses in
metropolitan areas, and the virus circulation in Brazil, make the ideal
conditions for an outbreak. Now the task for sanitary authorities is to
avoid an epidemic, such as the one in 1999 that put more than 150 000
persons in the hospital. The additional risk is that complications may
appear with dengue hemorrhagic fever in the case of a person who already
has the disease and gets infected with a viral serotype different from the
one that infected him/her the 1st time.
Dengue is a very particular disease, since it has the capacity for rapidly
disseminating. The disease is transmitted in places where there are
mosquito breeding sites. A single infected mosquito can fly up to 400
metres, and it is able to transmit the disease to a whole neighborhood.
There is no vaccine available to prevent dengue. The best way for
controlling it is to eliminate mosquito breeding sites. _Aedes aegypti_
lives near houses; it prefers clean water, and it lays its eggs in flower
vases, plates under plant pots, water fountains for animals, tanks, and
water channels. "It is important to remember that dengue is a community
problem. Preventing the disease means eliminating all mosquito breeding
sites," said Dr. Wima Basualdo, head of the Health Surveillance area.
Preventive measures are well known by the population, but they are usually
not put into practice. They basically consist of eliminating all clean
water reservoir(s). It is important to keep bottles upside down and pick up
all toys and cans from the yard. Every water container, such as flower pots
or water fountains for animals, must have its water contents changed every
day, and they must be cleaned with a sponge in order to destroy mosquito
eggs that may adhere to their walls. Used tires must be perforated and
buried. After each rainfall, it is important to wash out external water
ducts from households. It is also recommended to treat water from
out-of-use water fountains with chemicals (abate or temophos, car oil,
gasoil, or salt).
Fever, headache, retroocular pain, muscle pain and red spots on the skin
are characteristic signs of dengue. Since it may be confused with other
viral conditions, medical consultation must be sought, and a test must be
requested, which is free, from the Central Laboratory (Venezuela and
Florida). A blood test is usually performed 5 days after fever onset. Every
physician is obligated to notify suspected cases to the Ministry of Public
Health, phone: 203-998.
--
