[4] Philippines
Date: Tue 28 Mar 2006
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: The Mindanao Daily Mirror, Philippines, 27 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://bond.lanesystems.com/sitegen/article.asp?wid=125&cid=451&aid=36220>

Dengue downs 9 in Zambo, one killed
-----------------------------------
The Zamboanga City Health Office (CHO) wants an anti-dengue city-wide clean
up day in all 98 barangays in the city in preparation for the resurgence of
dengue disease this year [2006].
This was proposed after a 3 year old child from Sitio Luyahan, Barangay
Pasonanca died of dengue recently while under treatment at the Zamboanga
City Medical Center, City Health Officer Dr Rodel Agbulos reported.
The CHO has also noted that dengue has started to pick up in various towns,
after several new patients were admitted to the city hospital suspected of
having the disease, in addition to the 8 others previously recorded.
The massive clean-up drive, expected next month [April 2006] will require
residents to destroy all possible breeding grounds of [_Aedes aegypti_],
the transmitter of the fatal dengue. Dengue cases reached an alarming level
here last year [2005].
******
[5] Philippines
Date: March 27, 2006.
From: Alfonso Rodriguez, M.D.<ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Minda News, Philippines. 03/27/2006.
<http://www.mindanews.com/2006/03/27nws-dengue.htm>

NorthCot alarmed over rise in dengue cases
------------------------------------------
Health officials in the province of North Cotabato are alarmed over the
increase of cases of dengue fever in January and February.
Ely Nebrija, chief of the Dengue Control Division of the Integrated
Provincial Health Office (IPHO) said a total of 107 patients were admitted
in hospitals for dengue. Of this number, four died. Nebrija said the deaths
were documented in Kidapawan City and the towns of Mlang and Antipas.
Nebrija said Kidapawan City remains on top with a total of 35 cases
followed by M�lang and Antipas with 26 and 11 cases, respectively.
Vernon Qui�s, IPHO sanitation inspector, said these towns are
agricultural and have many swampy areas which could be breeding grounds of
the dengue-carrying mosquito. Qui�s has instructed the sanitary
inspectors in the affected areas to ensure cleanliness particularly in
swampy places.
In 2005 a total of 1,194 cases of hemorrhagic dengue fever were recorded in
district hospitals and private hospitals in the entire province. From
January to June last year, 673 cases of dengue were recorded in 5
government hospitals in the province. Based on the dengue surveillance
report of the IPHO, 16 people died from dengue last year in the province.
[byline: Williamor A Magbanua]
